#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:7
msgid "The cosmic distance ladder refers to the succession of different methods that astronomers use to measure distances to objects in the sky. Some methods, like :doc:`parallax  <ai-parallax>`, work well for only nearby objects. Other methods, like using the *cosmological redshift*, work only for very distance galaxies. Thus, there are several methods, each with its own limited validity, and hence the name."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:19
msgid "Direct measurements"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:21
msgid "The bottom of the ladder consists of objects whose distances can be directly measured, like the moon (see `Lunar Laser Ranging <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lunar_Laser_Ranging_experiment>`__). The same technique, using radio waves, is applied to find distances to planets as well."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:27
msgid "For nearby stars, measuring the :doc:`parallax  <ai-parallax>` is possible and yields the distance to the star."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:34
msgid "Standard candles"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:36
msgid "\"Standard candles\" are objects whose intrinsic brightnesses we can know for sure. The apparent :doc:`magnitude  <ai-magnitude>`, which is easy to measure, tells us how bright an object appears, not how bright it actually is. Distant objects appear less brighter, because their light gets spread out over a larger area."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:43
msgid "In accordance with the *inverse square law* for light intensities, the amount of light we receive from an object drops with the distance squared. Thus, we may compute the distance to an object if we know both how bright it actually is (absolute magnitude; 'M') and how bright it appears to us on earth (apparent magnitude; 'm'). We may define the *distance modulus* as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:51
msgid "Distance Modulus = M - m = 5 log\\ :sub:`10` d - 5"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:53
msgid "Here 'd' is the distance measured in :doc:`parsecs  <ai-parallax>`."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:56
msgid "For these special standard candle objects, we have some other way of knowing their intrinsic brightness, and thereby can calculate their distance."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:61
msgid "Cepheid Variables: A kind of periodic variable star, whose variation period is related to the luminosity"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/ai-cosmicdist.rst:64
msgid "RR Lyrae Variables: Another such periodic variable star with a well-known period-luminosity relationship"
msgstr ""

